While most host cities have seven years to prepare for the Olympic Games, Los Angeles will get an additional four, giving the city eleven years. The Los Angeles bid relied on a majority of existing venues; other venues that are already under construction or were planned regardless of the Games. [[Banc_of_California_Stadium|Banc of California Stadium]], which opened in 2018 as the home of [[Major_League_Soccer|Major League Soccer]]'s [[Los_Angeles_FC|Los Angeles FC]], will host [[association_football|football (soccer)]] and several events in [[Sport_of_athletics|athletics]]. [[SoFi_Stadium|SoFi Stadium]] (which will be named as '''Los Angeles Olympic Stadium''' during the Games{{citation needed|date=January 2022}}), which opened in 2020 as the home of the [[NFL|NFL]]'s [[Los_Angeles_Rams|Los Angeles Rams]] and [[Los_Angeles_Chargers|Los Angeles Chargers]], will host the main opening ceremony, football, and [[archery|archery]]. Around the time when Los Angeles won its bid, the [[Los_Angeles_Clippers|Los Angeles Clippers]] proposed building a [[Inglewood_Basketball_and_Entertainment_Center|new arena]] in Inglewood. However, this venue has not yet been approved and has yet to be mentioned as a potential Olympic venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2018/08/17/la-clippers-owner-steve-ballmer-says-team-needs-own-house-new-arena|title=LA Clippers owner Steve Ballmer still seeking Inglewood arena for team - NBA.com|first=From NBA media|last=reports|website=nba.com|access-date=August 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817171122/http://www.nba.com/article/2018/08/17/la-clippers-owner-steve-ballmer-says-team-needs-own-house-new-arena|archive-date=August 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://la.curbed.com/2018/6/19/17480328/inglewood-lawsuit-clippers-arena-housing|title=Inglewood residents sue to block Clippers arena|website=curbed.com|date=June 19, 2018|access-date=August 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724111808/https://la.curbed.com/2018/6/19/17480328/inglewood-lawsuit-clippers-arena-housing|archive-date=July 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

The [[Los_Angeles_Memorial_Coliseum|Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] underwent a major renovation and restoration program from 2017 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/multimedia/USC-Trojans-Football-Los-Angeles-Memorial-Coliseum-Renovation-Changes-470903743.html|title=See the Changes Coming to the Historic LA Memorial Coliseum|publisher=[[NBCUniversal|NBCUniversal Media]]|date=January 29, 2018|access-date=March 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323092706/https://www.nbclosangeles.com/multimedia/USC-Trojans-Football-Los-Angeles-Memorial-Coliseum-Renovation-Changes-470903743.html|archive-date=March 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A new press box, [[Box_(theatre)|loge boxes]], and club seats were installed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coliseumrenovation.com/news/renovated-coliseum-press-box-be-named-otis-booth-press-box|title=Renovated Coliseum Press Box to be Named Otis Booth Press Box|publisher=The Coliseum Renovation Project|access-date=April 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414234739/http://coliseumrenovation.com/news/renovated-coliseum-press-box-be-named-otis-booth-press-box|archive-date=April 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This reduced stadium capacity from 93,607 to 78,467.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.usc.edu/135477/united-airlines-memorial-coliseum-to-be-new-name-for-l-a-landmark/|title=United Airlines Memorial Coliseum to be new name for L.A. landmark - USC News. January 29, 2018|website=www.usc.edu|date=January 29, 2018|access-date=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806203852/http://news.usc.edu/135477/united-airlines-memorial-coliseum-to-be-new-name-for-l-a-landmark/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As the track and field venue, future renovations include the re-installation of an athletics track.
